'Lady Anne Hamilton', painted in 1815 by James Lonsdale.
Bequeathed by Mrs. White, it now hangs in the British Galleries in the Victoria & Albert Museum, London.
Lady Anne Hamilton was a lady-in-waiting to the Princess of Wales, later Queen Caroline of Brunswick.
The unfortunate Queen was married to King George IV, who was notoriously unfaithful, and became grotesquely overweight in his final years. His father, King George III, died aged 81 in 1820, after 60 years on the throne. This meant that George IV became king at the age of 57, and at this point, his marriage to Queen Caroline had been in tatters for a long time. In fact, they had been separated for over 20 years. But, the Queen refused to divorce.
In 1820, as the old King George III died, George IV became King and thus Caroline became Queen.
She immediately left Italy (where she had lived for years after her separation from the King) for London to be rightfully, in her eyes, crowned Queen of the United Kingdom. The King however, hated her and had her banned from the coronation. She was refused entry to Westminster Abbey, and there was even a bill introduced in Parliament to strip her off her rightful title as Queen. But, due to the popularity of Caroline, it was blocked in the House of Commons.
After the Queen's public scandal and shame, she died within a year after.
To avoid riots and displays of support for the Queen, the traditional funeral procession through Central London was cancelled. There was an attempt to sneak the body of the popular Queen out of London unnoticed, but this was found out, which lead to even more violent protests in the streets than anticipated, which lead to two men being killed after the public threw rocks and spat at soldiers. Because of this, the cortège was, in the end, taken through the city.
And what was left by the Queen in her will to her loyal servant, the Lady Anne, after she had stood by her Queen faithfully through all this...?
A portrait. Of Queen Caroline.

Upon reflection I think I’d be inclined to call 2018 ”the year of natural cooperation”. So much in my professional life, I feel, was achieved particularly because of great cooperation, which also led to some even greater things for 2019. 
Thank you, Mark Gregory and Nigel Dunnett for continuing significant professional support and inspiration, which will result in the first ever Finnish Garden design at the Chelsea Flower Show 2019: The Roots in Finland Kyrö Garden. The cooperation with my team and sponsors to make it happen is well underway. 
Thank you dear colleagues of the University of Helsinki Fifth Dimension (Viides ulottuvuus) Research Group for the heart-felt camaraderie and all the magnificent work on the award winning Greenest of the Green apartment building project, which, we now know, will spawn a new era in urban greening. 
Last but not least, the foundation for the aforementioned cooperation is the team work at home, with the family. Everything else stems from that. A big thank you to my loved ones! ⭐️🥂⭐️Wishing everyone a very Happy New Year!

American Fable is a 2016 American thriller film written and directed by Anne Hamilton. The film follows a young girl who is forced to choose between saving an innocent man’s life or protect her family and their struggling farm.

Have you ever been travelling, whether by car, bus or train and during transit you see graffiti painted in a location that just makes you pause and go “how the hell did they get up there and why?”. That moment is how I would describe this film. You’re just left sitting there asking yourself “what was the point of that and what did I just watch?” because after watching it, even a day later I still have no idea what this film was trying to be.

If you were to go on the internet and search for a synopsis for the film it will say 2 things: 1. That the film is set in the 1980s and 2. “as the family finds itself involved with magical individuals who are like something out of a fairy tale”. Not once was it made clear during this film that it was set in the 1980s, I’m still not convinced that it was. The fashion was not 80s, nothing about this film said 80s. I suppose the only attempt at a reference was an old TV showing a speech by a former United States President Ronald Reagan, but this is not enough to establish an accurate timeline as like myself many can assume this was simply a look at an old speech. Also how many people around the world are going to recognise a President from the 80’s in a brief clip on a small old television? In regards to the synopsis talking about “magical individuals” there were no such characters. There was no magic or magical characters. The reason why one might make such an assumption is due to a figure who appears in the background, a black knight looking person on a black horse, with a porcelain mask and black ram horns on its head. It’s seen a total of perhaps 4 or 5 times during the film, only briefly trotting along in the corn fields and nothing more. It connects to the tone and plot of the film in no way, it is completely illogical. It’s the most bizarre and random aspect of this film.

In una Francia occupata dai nazisti, Hortensia, bella e viziata, vive insoddisfatta il suo matrimonio con Daniel Mayer, noto esperto d’arte, dal carattere cinico e ambizioso. Quando la guerra li costringe alla fuga, durante il viaggio conosce il giovane Jean Louis, un collaboratore di Daniel, e tra loro nasce un breve amore che annulla la ragione e sospende il tempo, fin quasi a far loro dimenticare la guerra in corso. Ma la guerra, invece finisce col separarli e Hortensia viene coinvolta in una complessa e oscura rete di vendette trasversali e tradimenti che ruotano attorno a un crimine commesso da Daniel e a tre preziosi disegni rubati. Sconvolta dalla svolta drammatica della sua vita, Hortensia assiste impotente al crollo delle sue certezze: tra le accuse di collaborazionismo e la scomparsa delle persone a lei più care, coltiva il ricordo del suo amore speciale per Jean Louis che non riuscirà mai a dimenticare. Fuga da Parigi è il racconto di un sentimento luminoso vissuto in un tempo di tragica oscurità. Tra le sue pagine prende vita un mondo in bilico tra realtà e finzione, una storia corale di epica quotidiana, fatta di sconfitte, desideri, nostalgia e speranza. Si erano gettati uno sull’altro in quei giorni, divorando la felicità che si davano senza tener conto delle conseguenze.

FÁBULA AMERICANA (2016)
Nota: 4 (de 5)
Direção: Anne Hamilton
Gênero: Thriller
País: EUA
Título original: American Fable

Sinopse: Na década de 1980, uma garota interiorana de 11 anos encontra um homem escondido no silo da fazenda da sua família. Ao fazer amizade com esse homem, ela precisa escolher entre salvar a vida dele ou proteger a sua família.

Miniresenha: Misto de drama familiar e suspense com uns toques sobrenaturais, "Fábula Americana" é um filme belíssimo, fotografado de maneira eficaz Wyatt Garfield - que abusa do recurso de "noite americana" para criar um clima fantasioso - e dirigido com segurança por Anne Hamilton, que constroi a sua narrativa instigando o espectador, sem esmiuçar as respostas, e abusando de metáforas que dão um sentido muito mais profundo para aquela história aparentemente simples. O ritmo pode soar um pouco lento demais em alguns momentos, mas isso é compensado pela atuação cativante da jovem Peyton Kennedy.

Seconda guerra mondiale? Fughe per salvarsi? Disegni che nascondono segreti o potrebbero segnare la rovina dei personaggi?
.
È la trama perfetta per me!
.
Se poi ci aggiungiamo pure che l'autrice ha preferito mantenere l'anonimato proprio per i fatti riportati nel suo romanzo, allora ogni mia resistenza (già nulla in realtà) cede del tutto.
.
Insomma, trama davvero interessante, ricca di dettagli, particolareggiata; ci si sposta persino di continente! 🤩
.
Tuttavia, non sono rimasta molto convinta dal modo in cui la storia viene condotta: in qualche punto ristagna e, sebbene si cominci con il botto e una bella dose di entusiasmo, non si riesce a mantenere costante il ritmo della narrazione che, a tratti, si fa un po' pesante intervallato poi da riflessioni personali ripetitive da parte dei personaggi.
.
E, non saprei, da una scrittrice mi sarei aspettata un tono, una sensibilità diversi... soprattutto con riferimento a certi temi che i personaggi si trovano ad affrontare... ma, essendo il nome della scrittrice uno pseudonimo scelto per mantenere la funzione letteraria, chissà chi si nasconde dietro (in certi passaggi ho avuto l'impressione che a scrivere fosse un uomo... ma ci sta che stia solo ammattendo! 🤪).
.
La storia prometteva davvero tanto (anche se poi i fantomatici disegni rubati, che parevano quasi centrali nella vicenda, hanno un ruolo davvero marginale) ma non riesce a mantenere queste promesse nella messa in pratica.
.
Davvero un peccato...
.
📚Ancora grazie all’ufficio stampa de @lanavediteseo che mi ha permesso di leggere questo romanzo! ❤️

American Fable (Anne Hamilton, 2017) 
Diving back into the indie scene with this Americana oddity, about a young girl living during the 1980’s Farm Crisis, who uncovers a plan by her father and brother to kidnap the property developer buying up all the land around them. It’s an unusual crime thriller of sorts, attempting to do a Pan’s Labyrinth by blending elements of Fantasia in the girls mind with the real life events going on around her, yet this is mostly shown through some rather poorly shot and edited dream sequences and the odd appearance of people wearing masks and riding horses. The “real-world” story also fails to draw any interest either, there’s very little insight into the actual agricultural crisis, nor do we get a real sense of emotional involvement (Especially in the final act, which fails to justify its dark and bloody tone when it arrives out of the blue). There’s some semi-decent cinematography of the rustic setting, and a rather nice turn from Peyton Kennedy in the lead role, but really it’s just a bit too half-baked to really go anywhere. #film #cinema #movie #filmblog #filmcollection #filmoftheday #filmmaking #filmreview #filmposter #filmtime #americanfable #annehamilton #2017 #peytonkennedy #richardschiff #kippardue #marcimiller #drama #thriller #crime #fantasy #indiefilm #independentfilm

#8of52 my eighth film by a female filmmaker is Anne Hamilton's American Fable. Peyton Kennedy is effortlessly endearing as the young lead, Gitty, a lonely young girl who submerged herself into a world of make believe in the midst of a horrifying situation. Choosing to hear stories over the truth, she unravels her family's dark secrets and it's ultimately up to her to decide what kind of warrior she wants to be. The film was incredible, a debut feature from Hamilton, incorporating elements of surrealism and fantasy in Gitty's world while maintaining the reality of the darkness lurking underneath. #52filmsbywomen #americanfable #annehamilton

This is Anne Hamilton’s new book. Anne weaves narration, geography, revelatory insights, sound teaching, prayers and discussion question, and photography/illustrations in this book. Interestingly, all of this is set and based in three regions that Jesus ministered in, and brought great healing to the people as well as the land. Shechem, Gadara and Galilee. If you follow Anne on social media, you know that she teaches about the connection between the healing of land and it’s people often. This book expands on that teaching and is packed with insight and wisdom. 
Thanks so much Anne for this lovely treasure! ❤️ I finally got to it and will be reading it a few more times.

Max Lucado once said, “when a potter fires a clay vessel, he checks its readiness by pulling it out of the furnace and thumping it. If it “sings” it’s ready. If it “thuds” it has to be put back in. 
James 1:2 says “Count it all joy when you fall into various trails...” There are many variety of “thumps” in life: flat tyres, burnt meals, traffic jams, long queues, grouchy people, impossible deadlines, dirty clothes on the floor, “nagging” children. 
None of these things is big enough to be a crisis but enough of them can trigger a violent over-reaction. “Character is checked by thumping”- Lucado
